metadata.name: Qoqnus #102
metadata.description:
Qoqnus

In ancient Greek: φοῖνιξ
In Arabic: Al-Anqa
In English: Phoenix

The sacred bird is a legend that is mentioned in Iranian mythology, Greek mythology, Egyptian mythology, and Chinese mythology.
It is said that he is a rare and lonely bird and does not mate or reproduce. But once every thousand years, it spreads its wings on a large pile of firewood and sings, and when it is excited by its song, it lights a fire with its beak, and by burning in the fire from its ashes, another phoenix is ​​born.
In many cultures, the phoenix is ​​considered a symbol of immortality, sacrifice and long life.

In this work, I tried to create bird-like shapes that are being formed and created by using a grid in the form of noise and with the shape of rectangles that have random length and width and get their color from the palettes. You can clearly see the wings or the bird's head in most of the exits
In fact, my idea is to depict the moment of resurrection and rebirth of the phoenix from the heart of the ashes, which rises to the sky.
the ash particles around this reborn bird are being scattered in the air and finally from At the heart of this re-creation, a beautiful and glorious phoenix comes into existence.

Made by p5.js

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #298
metadata.description:
“Shapes on a Plane” explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It’s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I’d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i’d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I’d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: PolyGarden #225
metadata.description:
Polygons, patterns and flowers are mixtured in my garden. I start with a birdeye view of the garden and its geometric structure. The species diversity and the random stack of rocks, sands, fences and other objects are main structures I want to capture, in an abstract and planar style. 

Moreover, in this project, I also try to explore the representation ability of generative art. I select three elements: shape of entity, layout of palette, and stack of object location. The factors behind these elements are the balance of randomness and structure: the generative art generates the variants from randomness but restricts its chaos with structure (deterministic constraints) to represent the meaningful results. 

Variables:
- 4 layouts
- 6 texture patterns
- 15 color palette
- 3 randomness
- 2 completeness

Please be patient with drawing process.

metadata.name: Seasons #97
metadata.description:
Seasons depicts monolithic mountains and calm seas scattered with unnatural elements.
The color palettes explore the colors of natural landscapes through different times of year.

To ease browser load, the images are paused by default.
Hitting 'p' will toggle a subtle animation.
Hitting 't' will toggle between the day and night palette for the image.
On mobile the resolution is reduced and the image is always paused to ease the load on the device.

Generative images by 0x3739
twitter.com/0x3739
library: twgljs - A Tiny WebGL helper Library
license: CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0
Tested and functioning correctly on Google Chrome version 100.0.4896.88 on Windows desktop and Android mobile device.

The work is rendered in webgl as a fragment shader.
Setting parameters in the javascript portion of the script generates a different fragment shader for each iteration.

Interactions
'-' to zoom in.
'+' to zoom out.
'f' to change the aspect ratio to fullscreen.
'z' to change the aspect ratio to square.
'a' to change the aspect ratio to A4/A3/A2/A1 format.
'w' to change the aspect ratio to 16:9.
'q' to change the aspect ratio to portrait.
's' to save an image of the canvas.
'p' to pause the animation the image.
't' to toggle the time (day/night) in the image.
'b' to toggle the margins on the image.
'm' to toggle the mountains in the image.
'c' to toggle the clouds in the image.
'g' to toggle the grid in the image.
'd' to toggle the dirt speckles in the image.
'n' to toggle the noise in the image.
'j' to toggle the jitter in the image.
'v' to toggle all vintage effects in the image.
'1' to toggle the stars in the image.
'2' to toggle the moons in the image.
'3' to toggle the black squares in the image.
'4' to toggle the white squares in the image.
'5' to toggle the primary color squares in the image.
'6' to toggle the secundary color squares in the image.
'7' to toggle the colour correction in the image.
'8' to toggle the sea in the image.
'h' to increase the quality modifier (maximum is 3).
'l' to decrease the quality modifier (minimum is 1).
The quality modifier is a modifier on the width and height of the canvas.
Changing the modifier can affect the look of the image due to subpixel artifacts.
The modifier can be used to save higher resolution images.
Higher values of the modifier increase memory usage and can cause a browser or webgl instance to crash. 
'arrow_up' to move up in the image.
'arrow_down' to move down in the image.
'arrow_right' to move right in the image.
'arrow_left' to move left in the image.

metadata.name: Rehash 10000 #446
metadata.description:
This project was supposed to be released in celebration of fxhash reaching 10,000 projects since its inception, but it's hard to celebrate when war breaks out and innocent people fear for their lives. Please go ahead and mint as many iterations as you like for free. If you feel the art is worth more than 0 tez, you are welcome to donate to the Tezos fund to support our Ukrainian friends (KT1DWnLiUkNtAQDErXxudFEH63JC6mqg3HEx).

Each mint combines 5 of my previous 14 fxhash projects into a drug-induced distorted vision of life in the Metaverse. This artwork is fully generative and was entirely hand-coded in 5333 lines of plain JavaScript code. Forever limited to 500 editions on the Tezos blockchain. London, February 2022.

metadata.name: Strata #218
metadata.description:
A generative series inspired by the work of Vera Molnár, Strata explores the diversity that can come from one shape - the simple rectangle.

With 16 properties and ~600 palettes, I hope that each mint offers something unique and special.

Exploration is fully open and will be left open post-mint :)

metadata.name: Brosser #155
metadata.description:
Exploring generative brush strokes to simulate real life paintings. 

- A selection of 19 different palettes
- 4 different drawing styles
- Randomized "color swap" between the primary and secondary colors in each palette

Several other factors determine the output of a piece, including angles, depth, brush length, and brush weight, among others.
